<p>
<seg id="1">TYDTA Chairman Ermut: Foreign direct investment will exceed last year’s.</seg>
<seg id="2">TYDTA Chairman, Arda Ermut, has indicated that 55% of all investment last year came after July.</seg>
<seg id="3">Relaying that there had been no decrease in investment following the July 15 FETÖ coup attempt and that, on the contrary, there had been an increase, Ermut said "Perhaps, it would have been more, but it was inhibited."</seg>
<seg id="4">If these conditions hadn’t arisen and some of the regional problems had not developed, we could have seen a greater increase with a multiplier effect.</seg>
<seg id="5">So we are more hopeful for the coming year.</seg>
<seg id="6">God Willing, it will be a much brighter year for direct investment.</seg>
<seg id="7">In the first five months, we have already grown 11% compared to the first five months of last year.</seg>
<seg id="8">But this is not enough.</seg>
<seg id="9">"We are hoping for more" he said.</seg>
<seg id="10">Adding that "we can’t say that we are not worried about both global and regional developments", Ermut stressed that they were trying to diversify their investors.</seg>
<seg id="11">Reiterating that, normally, until 2010, 75% of direct investment came from Europe, Ermut continued</seg>
<seg id="12">This figure has fallen to 66%.</seg>
<seg id="13">Still, Asia’s share went up from 2% to 7–8%.</seg>
<seg id="14">Russia’s share increased.</seg>
<seg id="15">While we were working to achieve this, some issues came up among the Gulf nations.</seg>
<seg id="16">Turkey has relations with all of them; Saudi Arabia and Qatar especially are two important actors.</seg>
<seg id="17">However, the problems between those two countries are worrying us and naturally this causes investors to postpone their decisions somewhat more.</seg>
<seg id="18">This is not only about investments in Turkey, but because of this we could be experiencing some delays.</seg>
<seg id="19">Ermut recollected that in the last weeks some developments had taken place in Germany but the government, especially President Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, had displayed a clear reaction to the situation.</seg>
<seg id="20">When we talked with these countries’ investors, with whom the harshest political crisis is happening, President Erdoğan’s reaction was "Look, problems between governments are definitely not between the publics."</seg>
<seg id="21">Secondly, these people have come and invested in my country.</seg>
<seg id="22">For us, they are no different than Turkish companies.</seg>
<seg id="23">On the contrary, upon even the tiniest of their problems, they will come to us and we will resolve it.</seg>
<seg id="24">"We definitely won’t let them suffer" said Ermut, adding that they continued to support all investors with confidence.</seg>
<seg id="25">Ermut said "We can also give an assurance of this for the upcoming period."</seg>
<seg id="26">You will see that no German company, or any other investors coming from countries with which we have some political issues, will experience any difficulty.</seg>
<seg id="27">On the contrary, God Willing, we will try our best to increase investments coming from these countries.</seg>
<seg id="28">We think that investments coming from such places will increase.</seg>
<seg id="29">Certainly, political developments could sometimes affect the perception of an investment environment.</seg>
<seg id="30">"But, at this point, we will do the our part, try our best for our investors, and the perception of our investment environment will not be affected" he said, evaluating the situation.</seg>
<seg id="31">TYDTA Chairman Ermut explained that after the One Road One Belt strategy, China had more interest in Turkey, but that they expect the largest investment to come from the Gulf countries, if the problems in the Gulf are resolved.</seg>
<seg id="32">"In the relations with Germany, there isn’t one single investor saying ‘We had experienced some problems and are running away’." said Ermut, adding that there had been potential, entering and other companies that they had been monitoring.</seg>
<seg id="33">Ermut said "At the moment, around 10% of the projects in our portfolio belong to German companies."</seg>
<seg id="34">That is to say, almost 10% of the companies that we are in contact with around the world are composed of German companies.</seg>
<seg id="35">Some of these already invest in Turkey.</seg>
<seg id="36">If someone is going to increase their investment, or if they have an issue, then for us that project is still open.</seg>
<seg id="37">"Therefore, in fact, German companies still compose a significant part of our daily workflow" he said.</seg>
<seg id="38">Stressing that all state institutions should be careful during a time in which there are perception management operations being undertaken against Turkey, Ermut said that the issue was serious and that it could be affected by the tiniest communication.</seg>
<seg id="39">Commenting on the events of the past 2–3 weeks, that there was a good lesson to be learned, Ermut said</seg>
<seg id="40">Investors’ and politicians’ agendas have always been different.</seg>
<seg id="41">We have always seen it this way, that economic relationships put political relationships onto their path, in a sense.</seg>
<seg id="42">Germany is an important trade partner of ours and will remain a significant investor.</seg>
<seg id="43">That is because they already have several investments.</seg>
<seg id="44">Unfortunately, the election agenda in Germany is increasing such rhetoric.</seg>
<seg id="45">I believe that once it is over, these issues will return to their path.</seg>
<seg id="46">In particular with regards to Saudi Arabia, both countries are paying special attention to not make any negative public statements.</seg>
<seg id="47">After all, an investor is investing in Turkey because he is targeting the neighboring markets.</seg>
<seg id="48">Therefore, there is a bit of a slow down in the processes, not because of Saudi Arabia, but because of the uncertainty in the region.</seg>
<seg id="49">But our communications with investors continue.</seg>
<seg id="50">It is my personal view that at the moment investors might be holding back on decisions that they could actually make much faster.</seg>
<seg id="51">"In the negative sense of the meaning, we have no Saudi investor saying "I see some uncertainty because of the crisis between Turkey and Saudi Arabia, hence I am exiting the market".</seg>
<seg id="52">On the contrary, we have several Saudi investors, whose processes we are currently following, who continue to live in Turkey, spend their holidays here, and are in contact with us.</seg>
<seg id="53">Bringing to mind that last year the international direct investments (UDY) in Turkey were 12.3 billion USD, Arda Ermut said "I definitely believe that we will surpass that this year.</seg>
<seg id="54">"But, how much we will surpass this by will be affected by global uncertainties".</seg>
<seg id="55">While normally hoping for a multiplier effect, this could be a little bit more limited, Ermut said that they had had an increase of 11% in the first five months and that this could be preserved, "God Willing, if there are no such negative developments, one way or another, I definitely believe that we will close this year much better than last year".</seg>
<seg id="56">Pointing out the fact that a significant proportion of the investments that were withdrawn would continue to be in the real estate sector, Ermut shared information detailing that new investments could be witnessed in logistics, health, fintech, information technology, petrochemicals, food, energy and manufacturing.</seg>
<seg id="57">Underlining the new investments that they would be announcing in the coming months, he said "In the near future, we might have an announcement to make in the manufacturing field."</seg>
<seg id="58">It will not be a billion dollar one, but a big investment.</seg>
<seg id="59">"There could be investments coming from interesting countries" Ermut commented.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
