<p>
<seg id="1">A "Seniority" issue in the Turkish army</seg>
<seg id="2">Dear readers, during the Supreme Military Council held the day before yesterday, interesting decisions were taken, especially from the perspective of the Turkish Naval Forces.</seg>
<seg id="3">A vice-admiral, not a full admiral, was brought in to command of the Force.</seg>
<seg id="4">This practice has virtually never been seen in our army.</seg>
<seg id="5">So, how did this happen?</seg>
<seg id="6">The Force Commander, Full Admiral Bülent Bostanoğlu, had completed his term and would retire anyway...</seg>
<seg id="7">And he did.</seg>
<seg id="8">Now the order for the commandership was due for only remaining full admiral, that is Veysel Kösele.</seg>
<seg id="9">Victimized by a plot in the past and imprisoned for some time, Admiral Kösele was, according to normal seniority, supposed to become the commander.</seg>
<seg id="10">But, the government did not want him.</seg>
<seg id="11">I am trying to explain briefly, starting from the top, how the number 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5 commanders in the Naval Forces were not promoted.</seg>
<seg id="12">In this case, there was only one full admiral in the Naval Forces left.</seg>
<seg id="13">He was supposed to have been appointed to the vacant position. That is number two, Fleet Commander Full Admiral Veysel Kösele.</seg>
<seg id="14">What happened then?</seg>
<seg id="15">The government appointed Vice-admiral Adnan Özbal, sixth in rank, to the position.</seg>
<seg id="16">Now, look at this scene!</seg>
<seg id="17">Full Admiral Veysel Kösele is there, but a commander of a lower rank is appointed in his place!</seg>
<seg id="18">A senior is subordinated to the junior one.</seg>
<seg id="19">I wonder what will happen next?</seg>
<seg id="20">A full admiral, higher in rank, cannot perform his duties under a lieutenant general, who is his junior.</seg>
<seg id="21">He won’t and can’t take orders from him.</seg>
<seg id="22">In this case, Veysel Kösele would not tolerate this painful behavior, he would resign today or tomorrow, and if not, he will be retired.</seg>
<seg id="23">Already, this is the government’s painful message to him: "Good bye Veysel Admiral!"</seg>
<seg id="24">When I wrote this piece, rumors were spread about his resigning in the afternoon, but nothing was officially announced.</seg>
<seg id="25">Now, let’s look at what happened!</seg>
<seg id="26">The government for one reason or another opposed Veysel Kösele, did not want him, forced him to resign and appointed a vice-admiral, sixth in rank, to the commandership in his place, the government damaged the army’s traditional "seniority" concept.</seg>
<seg id="27">There is definitely politics in this and we cannot know what is behind the scenes.</seg>
<seg id="28">May be some day, if someone talks about it, we will learn!</seg>
<seg id="29">Dear readers, as I have tried to explain briefly above, the issue of seniority is of paramount importance.</seg>
<seg id="30">Not just as a rank.</seg>
<seg id="31">For example, an officer finishing tenth in rank in the Military Academy is more senior than the one finishing eleventh.</seg>
<seg id="32">One promoted to generalship from the first rank is more senior than the one promoted from the second rank.</seg>
<seg id="33">We experienced of concrete examples of this seniority issue during the Independence War.</seg>
<seg id="34">The commander of the Western Front İsmet Paşa...</seg>
<seg id="35">He had two armies under his command.</seg>
<seg id="36">The Army and the Second Army.</seg>
<seg id="37">Here we were in 1922, our armies were about to make a major assault and chase the Greek army away.</seg>
<seg id="38">At this stage, there were other valuable names to be appointed to the army’s commandership.</seg>
<seg id="39">One of them was Refet (Bele) Pasha.</seg>
<seg id="40">He was offered the army commandership, but he said "İsmet is junior to me, I cannot go under his command".</seg>
<seg id="41">Another is Yakup Şevki (Subaşı) Pasha.</seg>
<seg id="42">Atatürk’s instructor from the Military Academy...</seg>
<seg id="43">Much loved and valued, called "Hocam", he was a commander who had partaken in various battles, a valuable and senior commander.</seg>
<seg id="44">In 1919, the military and civilian Turkish intellectuals were together caught by the British and banished to the island of Malta.</seg>
<seg id="45">On his return to the country, he was also unwilling to taking take the army’s commandership, uttering the same words: "The commander of the western front is junior to me, and I cannot take orders from him".</seg>
<seg id="46">But, Atatürk convinced him and Yakup Şevki Pasha assumed the commandership of one of our two armies.</seg>
<seg id="47">The third one has a very colorful name...</seg>
<seg id="48">Ali İhsan (Sabis) Pasha.</seg>
<seg id="49">A talkative, continuously criticizing soldier.</seg>
<seg id="50">A commander who fought in Iraq, the Caucasus, Iran and on various fronts.</seg>
<seg id="51">He was also banished to Malta by the British, though he escaped from there and went to Kuşadası and then to Ankara.</seg>
<seg id="52">When he was offered the army’s commandership, the same things were also uttered by Ali İhsan Paşa: "İsmet is junior to me, and I cannot fight under his command"...</seg>
<seg id="53">But, he was convinced...</seg>
<seg id="54">But, after starting his duty, he continuously argued with the commander of Western Front, İsmet Pasha, whom he was subordinated to, creating a scene and disturbing the peace in the army...</seg>
<seg id="55">Shortly before the great offensive, he was discharged and retired, and Nurettin Pasha was brought in in his place.</seg>
<seg id="56">Later, Ali İhsan Pasha never got along with Atatürk.</seg>
<seg id="57">The seniority issue in the Turkish army is not only an issue at war, but also in peace.</seg>
<seg id="58">And, naturally, it should be.</seg>
<seg id="59">Veysel Kösele is the latest example of this.</seg>
</p>
</doc>
